[[Royal Republic]]<br />\n[[All Time Low]]<br />\n|}\n\n==2014 festival==\nThe 2014's edition of Rock am Ring was spread over 4 days.\nHeadliners: [[Iron Maiden]], [[Kings of Leon]], [[Linkin Park]], [[Metallica]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-2014-mit-vier-assen |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129102018/http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-2014-mit-vier-assen |archivedate=November 29, 2013 }}</ref> Other bands included [[Alligatoah]], [[Alter Bridge]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Babyshambles]], [[Booka Shade]], [[Die Fantastischen Vier]], [[Fall Out Boy]], [[Ghost (Swedish band)|Ghost]], [[Gogol Bordello]], [[Heaven Shall Burn]], [[In Extremo]], [[Jake Bugg]], [[Jan Delay & Disko No. 1]], [[John Newman (singer)|John Newman]], [[Karnivool]], [[Klangkarussell Live]], [[Kvelertak]], [[Left Boy]], [[Mando Diao]], [[Marteria]], [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]], [[Max\u00efmo Park]], [[Milky Chance]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[Of Mice & Men (band)|Of Mice & Men]], [[Opeth]], [[Portugal. The Man]], [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Rob Zombie]], [[Rudimental]], [[SDP (band)|SDP]], [[Sierra Kidd]], [[Slayer]], [[Suicide Silence]], [[Teesy]], [[Triggerfinger]], [[The Offspring]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-motivieren-die-fans |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214211050/http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-motivieren-die-fans |archivedate=December 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Center Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Thursday, 5\n!Friday, 6\n!Saturday, 7\n!Sunday, 8\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Iron Maiden]]'''<br />\n[[The Offspring]] <br />\n[[Pennywise (band)|Pennywise]] <br />\n[[Falling in Reverse]] <br />\n[[Klangkarussell]] <br />\n[[Rudimental]] <br />\n[[Cro (rapper)|Cro]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Kings Of Leon]]'''<br />\n[[Mando Diao]] <br />\n[[Kasabian]] <br />\n[[Rea Garvey]] <br />\n[[Jake Bugg]] <br />\n[[John Newman (singer)|John Newman]] <br />\n[[Rival Sons]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Linkin Park]]'''<br />\n[[Die Fantastischen Vier]] <br />\n[[Fall Out Boy]] <br />\n[[Alligatoah]] <br />\n[[Kaiser Chiefs]] <br />\n[[The Pretty Reckless]] <br />\n[[257ers]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Metallica]]'''<br />\n[[Avenged Sevenfold]] <br />\n[[Alter Bridge]] <br />\n[[In Extremo]] <br />\n[[Trivium (band)|Trivium]] <br />\n[[Black Stone Cherry]] <br />\n|}\n\n==2015 festival==\nIn 2015 the festival moved to a new location, [[Mendig Air Base]] \nHeadliners: [[Foo Fighters]], [[Die Toten Hosen]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Motionless in White]].<ref name=\"rock-am-ring.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rock-am-ring.com/2015/bands |title=Lineup 2016 - Rock am Ring 2016 |publisher=Rock-am-ring.com |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> Other bands included [[A Day to Remember]], [[Asking Alexandria]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]], [[Body Count (band)|Body Count]] Feat. [[Ice-T]], [[Eagles of Death Metal]], [[Enter Shikari]], [[Godsmack]], [[Hollywood Undead]], [[In Flames]], [[Interpol (band)|Interpol]], [[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]], [[Marilyn Manson]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Parkway Drive]], [[Pop Evil]], [[Rise Against]], [[Royal Republic]], [[Skindred]], [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Three Days Grace]], [[Yellowcard]] and [[Zebrahead]].<ref name=\"rock-am-ring.com\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Volcano Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 5\n!Saturday, 6\n!Sunday, 7\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Die Toten Hosen]]''' <br />\n[[Rise Against]] <br />\n[[Broilers (band)|Broilers]] <br />\n[[A Day to Remember]]'''<br />\n[[Bad Religion]] <br />\n[[Yellowcard]] <br />\n[[Donots]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[The Prodigy]]'''<br />\n[[Kraftklub]] <br />\n[[Slash Feat. Myles Kennedy]] <br />\n[[Interpol (band)|Interpol]] <br />\n[[Royal Republic]] <br />\n[[Zebrahead]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Foo Fighters]]'''<br />\n[[Beatsteaks]] <br />\n[[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] <br />\n[[Frank Turner]] <br />\n[[Eagles of Death Metal]] <br />\n[[Ruen Brothers]]<br />\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Crater Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 5\n!Saturday, 6\n!Sunday, 7\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n[[Fritz Kalkbrenner]] <br />\n[[Marilyn Manson]] <br />\n[[Clueso]] <br />\n[[Tocotronic]]'''<br />\n[[Mighty Oaks (band)|Mighty Oaks]] <br />\n[[Jamie T]] <br />\n[[Ms Mr]] <br />\n[[T\u00fcsn]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n[[Marsimoto]] <br />\n[[Deichkind]] <br />\n[[K.I.Z]] <br />\n[[Prinz Pi]] <br />\n[[Trailerpark]] <br />\n[[Bilderbuch]] <br />\n[[Feine Sahne Fischfilet]] <br />\n[[Antilopen Gang]] <br />\n[[Zugezogen Maskulin]] <br />\n[[Sondaschule]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]'''<br />\n[[Mot\u00f6rhead]] <br />\n[[In Flames]] <br />\n[[Parkway Drive]] <br />\n[[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]] <br />\n[[Papa Roach]] <br />\n[[Godsmack]] <br />\n|}\n\n==2016 festival==\nThe festival was cancelled during the second day due to severe thunderstorms.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.welt.de/vermischtes/article155967447/Festival-Rock-am-Ring-wird-endgueltig-abgebrochen.html | title= Festival \"Rock am Ring\" wird endg\u00fcltig abgebrochen}}</ref>\n\n==2017 festival==\nIn 2017 the festival returned to the [[N\u00fcrburgring]].\nHeadliners: [[Rammstein]], [[Die Toten Hosen]] and [[System of a Down]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/history/2017|title=History - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 2 June 2017, the first day of the festival, the sold out event with about 85,000 visitors was interrupted at 9:00 pm during a performance by the [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] band [[Broilers (band)|Broilers]] and the festival grounds cleared. The reason given was a terrorist situation. Other scheduled performances for Friday evening, including those of the headliner [[Rammstein]] and the rapper [[Marteria]], were cancelled.<ref>[http://www.sueddeutsche.de/panorama/festival-in-der-eifel-musikfestival-rock-am-ring-vorlaeufig-unterbrochen-1.3533703 ''Musikfestival \u201eRock am Ring\u201c vorl\u00e4ufig unterbrochen.''], ''Sueddeutsche.de''. 2 June 2017</ref> Three men were arrested and checked in [[Hesse]] that same evening. Two of the men assigned to the [[Salafist]] scene in Hesse had access rights in the form of bracelets, which gave them direct access to many festival areas. One of the men was also suspected of having links to the terrorist scene. However, on the morning of 3 June, after a search of the grounds and a raid of the suspect's homes, the police announced that the suspicion of a threatening attack had not been substantiated, so that the festival could continue on Saturday noon. The access rights to the festival site had been received by the two main suspects due to a short-term staffing request from an external security service provider.<ref>[http://www.faz.net/aktuell/gesellschaft/kriminalitaet/verkehrskontrolle-fuehrte-zu-rock-am-ring-abbruch-15048628.html ''Verkehrskontrolle f\u00fchrte zu \u201eRock am Ring\u201c-Abbruch.''], ''faz.net'', 6 June 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Die Hintergr\u00fcnde zum Terroralarm bei Rock am Ring|periodical=Spiegel Online|url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/justiz/rock-am-ring-warum-es-einen-terror-alarm-gab-die-rekonstruktion-a-1150997.html|accessdate=2017-06-07|last=J\u00f6rg Diehl|date=2017-06-07}}</ref>\n\n==2018 festival==\nThe 2018 festival took place again in N\u00fcrburgring. Headliners: [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[Muse (band)|Muse]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Marilyn Manson]], and [[Gorillaz]].<ref>[http://www.rock-am-ring.com/history/2018 2018]. ''Rock am Ring'' (official website). Retrieved 4 June 2018.</ref>\n\n==2019 festival==\nThe 2019 festival took place once again in N\u00fcrburgring. Headliners:[[Tool (band)| Tool]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Die \u00c4rzte|Die \u00c4rzte,]] and [[Slayer (band)|Slayer]].<ref>https://www.rock-am-ring.com/history/2019</ref> Out of the 77 artists in the lineup, 36 percent were rock bands, equally representing alternative rock, hard rock, and indie rock, and 29 percent were metal bands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.viberate.com/article/how-rock-are-you-the-best-festivals-for-headbangers/|title=How Rock Are You? The Best Festivals for Headbangers|last=Klancnik|first=Urban|date=10 December 2019|website=Viberate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Update section|date=June 2018}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Rock am Ring 2006.jpg|Rock am Ring 2006 stage, Dir en grey shown\nFile:Rock am ring 2007 mainstage.jpg|Rock am Ring 2007 main stage, 30 Seconds to Mars\nFile:20080606 rock im park alternative stage panorama.jpg|Panorama from the Alternative Stage in Rock Im Park 2008 festival.\nFile:20080608 rockimpark zeppelinfield panorama.jpg|Panorama from the Zeppelin Field Main Stage during the Rock Im Park 2008 event.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Rock am Ring}}\n{{commons category|Rock im Park}}\n* [http://www.rock-am-ring.com Official Rock am Ring site]\n* [http://www.rock-im-park.com Official Rock im Park site]\n* [http://www.ringrocker.com Ringrocker.com]\n* [http://www.parkrocker.net Parkrocker.net]\n* [http://www.rockpalast.de/konzerte/2007/rock_am_ring/ Rockpalast \u2013 Rock am Ring 2007]\n* [http://www.newmixes.com/live_at_rock_am_ring-0601-0603-dab-2007.html Rock am Ring live sets audio files archive, Rockpalast broadcast]\n\n{{Rock festival}}\n\n[[Category:Heavy metal festivals in Germany]]\n[[Category:Concert tours]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1985]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox music festival\n| music_festival_name = {{lang|de|Rock am Ring}}<br/>{{lang|de|Rock im Park}}\n| image               = [[File:Prodigy-rock-am-ring-2009.jpg|250px|English group, The Prodigy performing at the 2009 Rock am Ring Festival, in N\u00fcrburg, Germany]]\n| caption             = [[The Prodigy]] performing at Rock am Ring 2009\n| location            = '''Rock am Ring''': [[N\u00fcrburgring]], [[N\u00fcrburg]], [[Rhineland-Palatinate]], [[Germany]]<br/>'''Rock im Park''': [[Zeppelinfeld]], [[Nuremberg]], [[Bavaria]], [[Germany]]\n| years_active        = 1985\u2013present\n| founders            = \n| dates               = Usually first weekend in June\n| genre               = [[Alternative rock]], [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]], [[punk rock]], [[electronic music|electronic]]\n| website             = '''Rock am Ring''': {{URL|http://www.rock-am-ring.com/en}} <br/>'''Rock im Park''': {{URL|http://www.rock-im-park.com/en}}\n}}\n\nThe '''{{lang|de|Rock am Ring}}''' ([[German language|German]] for \"Rock at the Ring\") and '''{{lang|de|Rock im Park}}''' (\"Rock in the Park\") festivals are two simultaneous [[rock music]] festivals held annually. While ''Rock am Ring'' takes place at the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] race track, ''Rock im Park'' takes place at the [[Zeppelinfeld]] in [[N\u00fcrnberg]].\n\nBoth festivals are usually regarded as one event with a mostly identical lineup for both festivals. All artists perform one day at [[N\u00fcrburgring]] and another day in N\u00fcrnberg during the three-day event. There have been minor exceptions in the past years where an artist would be announced for one of the festivals only. Combined, Rock im Park and Rock am Ring are the largest music festivals held in Germany and one of the largest in the world with a combined attendance of over 150,000 people in 2007, selling out both events in advance for the first time.<ref>Robertson, Joel (17 November 2014). [http://www.festicket.com/magazine/top-13-best-rock-and-metal-festivals-europe/ TOP 13: Rock and Metal Festivals in Europe] ''festicket.com''. Retrieved on 18 August 2015.</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:13-06-07 RaR Cro 01.jpg|thumb|Center Stage 2013, the German rapper [[Cro (rapper)|Cro]] performing]]\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde - Rock am RIng 2017-AL1779.jpg|thumb|Festival site Rock am Ring 2017]]\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde - Rock am Ring 2017-AL3764.jpg|thumb|Festival site Rock am Ring 2017]]\n[[File:Festivalgel\u00e4nde - Rock am Ring 2017-AL3849.jpg|thumb|Festival site Rock am Ring 2017]]\nRock am Ring was originally planned as a one-time festival on the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] celebrating the inauguration of a newer, shorter version of the race track in 1985, but due to its commercial success (with 75,000 audience members), it was decided to make the concert an annual event. However, after a dip in attendance for the 1988 event, the festival was put on hiatus for two years. In 1991, the festival returned with a new concept: as well as featuring well-known artists, event organizers present lesser known up-and-coming bands to the public. In 1993, Rock im Park took place for the first time in [[Vienna]]. For the 1994 event, Rock im Park moved to the disused [[Munich-Riem airport]], and the following year to Munich's [[Olympic Stadium (Munich)|Olympiastadion]], where it found a home for the 1995 and 1996 event. 1997 Rock im Park moved to Nuremberg's [[Frankenstadion]] where it was held until the venue was unavailable in 2004 because the stadium was being renovated for the [[2006 Football World Cup]]. Since 2004 the venue moved again to the current Zeppellinfeld, where Rock im Park was since held with the exception of the 2006 festival, which was moved to the Luitpoldhain.\n\nThe 2007 festival was used in a science experiment to test the effects of large bodies of people simultaneously jumping. The experiment data was used to calculate the result if the entire Chinese population were to jump in unison. The experiment concluded no significant results would come from the theoretical event.<ref>{{cite web | title=Rock Festival as Human Experiment (dead link as of 2011-11-25) | work=blog.sciam.com | url=http://blog.sciam.com/index.php?title=rock_festival_as_human_experiment_hip_ho&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1&ref=rss | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070713222937/http://blog.sciam.com/index.php?title=rock_festival_as_human_experiment_hip_ho&more=1&c=1&tb=1&pb=1&ref=rss | archivedate=2007-07-13 }}</ref>\n\nAfter 29 editions of Rock am Ring, the new owner of the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] decided that the contract would not be extended. The festival continued at another location in 2015 and 2016 ([[Mendig Air Base|Mendig Air Base/Vulkaneifel]]),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mlk.com/news/2990 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=July 13, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140715004726/http://www.mlk.com/news/2990 |archivedate=July 15, 2014 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.rock-am-ring.com/2015/news/wir-sind-der-ring Wir sind der Ring!] auf rock-am-ring.com</ref> returning to the [[N\u00fcrburgring]] in 2017.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/2017/news/rock-am-ring-zurueck-zum-nuerburgring |title=Rock am Ring zur\u00fcck zum N\u00fcrburgring |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161205235118/http://www.rock-am-ring.com/2017/news/rock-am-ring-zurueck-zum-nuerburgring |archivedate=2016-12-05 }}</ref>\n\n===Venues===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"t