ent]], [[Korn]], [[Broiler (music producers)|Broilers]], [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[The Offspring]], [[Weezer]], [[Bilderbuch]], [[Wanda (band)|Wanda]], [[Alan Walker (music producer)|Alan Walker]], [[Heaven Shall Burn]], [[Yungblud]], [[Powerwolf]], [[Of Mice & Men (band)|Of Mice & Men]], [[Motionless in White]], [[August Burns Red]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|-\n|- style=\"background:#dcdcdc;\"\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| 5\u20137 August<br/>2021<br/>\n|  | headliners [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[The Who]], [[Atreyu]], [[Megadeth]], [[Five Finger Death Punch]], [[U2]], [[Paul McCartney]], Ringo Starr & His All Starr Band, [[Bullet For My Valentine]], [[Smile (band)|Smile]]; also [[Tool (band)|Tool]], [[Slayer]], [[Tenacious D]], [[The Smashing Pumpkins]], [[Bring Me the Horizon]], [[Dropkick Murphys]], [[Sabaton (band)|Sabaton]], [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[REO Speedwagon]], [[Saga (band)|Saga]], [[Jefferson Starship]], [[System of a Down]], [[Green Day]], [[Volbeat]], [[Van Halen]], [[Bon Jovi]], [[Mettalica]], [[Elton John]], [[Fleetwood Mac]], [[Toto (band)|Toto]], [[Sting (musician)|Sting]], [[Saga (band)|Saga]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Rhythm Light Orchestra]], [[Deep Purple]], [[INXS]], [[Faith No More]], [[Def Leppard]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Rage Against The Machine]], [[Led Zeppelin]], [[The Grateful Dead]], [[Guns N' Roses]], [[Danzig (band)|Danzig]], [[The Black Crowes]], [[Aerosmith]], [[Peter Gabriel]], [[Clawfinger]], [[The Smashing Pumpkins]], [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[The Offspring]], [[Weezer]], [[Bilderbuch]], [[Wanda (band)|Wanda]], [[Kiss (band)|Kiss]], [[Bryan Adams]], [[Dave Matthews Band]], [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]], [[Lady Gaga]], [[John Prine]], [[The Band]], [[Bush (band)|Bush]], [[Mike + The Mechanics]], [[Sepultura]], [[Rancid (band)|Rancid]], [[Paradise Lost (band)|Paradise Lost]], [[Meat Loaf]], [[Soraya (musician)|Soraya]], [[Bonzo Dog Doo-Dah Band]], [[Die \u00c4rzte]], [[Supertramp]], [[Texas (band)|Texas]], [[Neneh Cherry]], [[Faith No More]], [[Bob Dylan]], [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], [[Ozzy Osbourne]], [[Rammstein]], [[Metallica]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Robbie Williams]], [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]], [[Blackmail (band)|Blackmail]], [[HIM (Finnish band)|HIM]], [[Anastacia]], [[Limp Bizkit]], [[Linkin Park]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Radiohead]], [[Alanis Morissette]], [[Kid Rock]], [[Godsmack]], [[OutKast]], [[Reamonn]], [[Hed PE]], [[Mudvayne]], [[Neil Young]], [[Santana]], [[Journey (band)|Journey]], [[Iron Maiden]], [[Audioslave]], [[Evanescence]], [[Apocalyptica]], [[Judas Priest]], [[John Mayall]], [[3 Doors Down]], [[DanTDM|Daniel Middleton]], [[Nickelback]], [[Billy Idol]], [[Brian May]], [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Amy Winehouse]], [[Trivium (band)|Trivium]], [[36 Crazyfists]], [[Panic! at the Disco]] and [[Alice in Chains]].\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| \n|}\n\n==2008 festival==\nThe 2008 festival took place on 6\u20138 June 2008. 91 acts have been officially confirmed. Both festivals were sold out on 1 May.\n\nConfirmed acts:\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=21|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=23|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=24|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=25|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=27|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=28|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"rock-am-ring.de\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.de/newsitem.html?objId=29|title=Live - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n<br/>\n[[3 Doors Down]] (replacing [[Chris Cornell]], who backed out to record an album<ref name=\"rock-am-ring.de\"/>), [[36 Crazyfists]], [[Against Me!]], [[Airbourne (band)|Airbourne]], [[Alpha Galates]], [[Alter Bridge]], [[Animal Alpha]], [[Babyshambles]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Bedouin Soundclash]], [[The Black Dahlia Murder (band)|The Black Dahlia Murder]], [[Black Stone Cherry]], [[Black Tide]], [[Bloodlights]], [[Booka Shade]], [[Bullet for My Valentine]], [[CSS (band)|CSS]], [[Cavalera Conspiracy]], [[Chiodos]], [[Coheed and Cambria]], [[Culcha Candela]], [[Danko Jones]], [[Die Toten Hosen]], [[Dimmu Borgir]], [[Disco Ensemble]], [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Eagles of Death Metal]], EL*KE, [[Fair to Midland]], [[Fettes Brot]], [[Fiction Plane]], [[Filter (band)|Filter]], [[Finger Eleven]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fingereleven.com/site/tourjournals.asp|title=Finger Eleven official website|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080508163555/http://www.fingereleven.com/site/tourjournals.asp|archivedate=2008-05-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myspace.com/fingereleven|title=Finger Eleven - Listen and Stream Free Music, Albums, New Releases, Photos, Videos|website=Myspace}}</ref> [[From First to Last]], [[Gavin DeGraw]], [[Gavin Rossdale]], [[High on Fire]], [[HIM (Finnish band)|HIM]], [[Hot Chip]], [[In Case of Fire]], [[In Flames]], [[Incubus (band)|Incubus]], [[Infadels]], [[Jimmy Eat World]], [[Joe Lean & The Jing Jang Jong]], [[Johnossi]], [[Jonathan Davis]], [[Justice (band)|Justice]], [[Kate Nash]], [[Kid Rock]], [[Kill Hannah]], [[Lostprophets]], [[Madsen (band)|Madsen]], [[Manic Street Preachers]], [[Masters of Reality]], [[Metallica]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Nightwish]], [[Oomph!]], [[Opeth]], [[Paramore]], [[Pete Murray (Australian singer-songwriter)|Pete Murray]], [[Queens of the Stone Age]], Rafael Weber, [[Rage Against the Machine]], [[Rival Schools (band)|Rival Schools]], [[R\u00f3is\u00edn Murphy]], [[Rooney (band)|Rooney]], [[Rose Tattoo]], [[Saul Williams]], [[Saxon (band)|Saxon]], [[Seether]], [[Serj Tankian]], [[Silverstein (band)|Silverstein]], [[Simple Plan]], [[S\u00f6hne Mannheims]], [[Sonic Syndicate]], [[Sportfreunde Stiller]], [[Stereophonics]], [[Steriogram]], [[Takida]], [[The Fall of Troy (band)|The Fall of Troy]], [[The Fratellis]], [[The Futureheads]], [[The Hellacopters]], [[The Offspring]], [[The Prodigy]], [[The Streets]], [[The Verve]], [[Tokyo Police Club]], [[Turisas]] and [[ZOX]].\n\nGlory of Joann's [http://profile.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=user.viewprofile&friendid=121562414 MySpace profile] lists them as performing at Rock am Ring, and [http://www.ringrocker.com/lineup.php?op=showall&menu=42&cat=22 ringrocker] lists them as officially confirmed.\n\n==2009 festival==\nThe headling acts for 2009 were '''[[Limp Bizkit]]''', '''[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]''', '''[[The Prodigy]]''', [[Ko\u042fn]], [[Marilyn Manson]], [[The Killers]], [[Placebo (band)|Placebo]] and [[Billy Talent]]. Other bands included [[2raumwohnung]], [[Alexisonfire]], [[All That Remains (band)|All That Remains]], [[...And You Will Know Us by the Trail of Dead]], [[Basement Jaxx]], [[Biffy Clyro]], [[Black Stone Cherry]], [[Bloc Party]], [[Bring Me the Horizon]], [[Chester French]], [[Chris Cornell]], [[Dir En Grey]], [[DragonForce]], [[Dredg]], [[Enter Shikari]], [[Esser (band)|Esser]], [[Expatriate (band)|Expatriate]], [[Five Finger Death Punch]], [[Flogging Molly]], Forbidden Theory, [[Gallows (band)|Gallows]], [[Guano Apes]], [[Hollywood Undead]], Ich Bin Bunt, [[Jan Delay]] & Disko No. 1, [[Juliette Lewis]], [[Kettcar]], [[Kilians]], [[Killswitch Engage]], [[Kitty, Daisy & Lewis]], [[Little Man Tate]], [[Machine Head (band)|Machine Head]], [[Madina Lake]], [[Madness (band)|Madness]], [[Mando Diao]], [[M.I.A. (artist)|M.I.A.]], [[Middle Class Rut]], [[New Found Glory]], [[Pain (musical project)|Pain]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Peter Bjorn and John]], [[Peter Fox (musician)|Peter Fox]], Phoenix, [[Polarkreis 18]], [[Razorlight]], [[Reamonn]], [[Scouting for Girls]], [[Selig (band)|Selig]], [[Sevendust]], [[Shinedown]], [[Staind]], [[Steadl\u00fcr]], [[Sugarplum Fairy]], [[The All-American Rejects]], [[The Crave]], [[The Gaslight Anthem]], [[The Kooks]], [[The Rifles]], [[The Script]], [[The Soundtrack of Our Lives]] (OEOC), [[The Subways]], [[Tomte (band)|Tomte]], [[Trivium (band)|Trivium]], [[Volbeat]], [[White Lies (band)|White Lies]]\nRock am Ring tickets were sold out by March 26.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-im-park.de/index.php?navi=1&rid=1&artid=583 |title=Live - Rock im Park 2016 |publisher=Rock-im-park.de |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n==2011 festival==\nThe headliners for the 2011 festival were [[System of a Down]], [[Coldplay]]. Other bands included [[Disturbed (band)|Disturbed]], [[Alter Bridge]], [[Rob Zombie]], [[Interpol (band)|Interpol]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Social Distortion]], [[Volbeat]], [[Beatsteaks]], [[August Burns Red]], [[The BossHoss]], [[Hurts]], [[Ko\u042fn]], [[Madsen (band)|Madsen]], [[Mando Diao]], [[The Kooks]], [[Sevendust]], [[In Flames]], [[3 Doors Down]], [[Lifehouse (band)|Lifehouse]], [[The Devil Wears Prada (band)|The Devil Wears Prada]], [[Ash (band)|Ash]] and [[The Gaslight Anthem]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Center Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 3\n!Saturday, 4\n!Sunday, 5\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Kings of Leon]]'''<br />\n[[Mando Diao]]<br />\n[[Social Distortion]] <br />\n[[The Gaslight Anthem]] <br />\n[[Plain White T's]] <br />\n[[We Are Scientists]] <br />\n[[Thees Uhlmann| Thees Uhlmann & Band]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Coldplay]]'''<br />\n[[S\u00f6hne Mannheims]]<br />\n[[The Kooks]]<br />\n[[Hurts]]<br />\n[[Ash (band)|Ash]]<br />\n[[The Naked and Famous]] <br />\n[[Morning Parade]]<br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[System of a Down]]'''<br />\n[[Beatsteaks]]<br />\n[[Volbeat]]<br />\n[[Avenged Sevenfold]]<br />\n[[Hollywood Undead]]<br />\n[[Millencolin]]<br />\n[[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]]<br />\n|}\n\n==2012 festival==\nActs for the 2012 edition included [[As I Lay Dying (band)|As I Lay Dying]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Awolnation]], [[Billy Talent]], [[Crystal Castles (band)|Crystal Castles]], [[Deichkind]], [[DevilDriver]], [[Dick Brave and the Backbeats]], [[Die Toten Hosen]], [[Donots]], [[Enter Shikari]], [[Evanescence]], [[Example (musician)|Example]], [[Gossip (band)|Gossip]], [[Gojira (band)|Gojira]], [[Guano Apes]], [[Kasabian]], [[Keane (band)|Keane]], [[KoRn]], [[The Koletzkis]], [[Killswitch Engage]], [[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]], [[Lexy & K-Paul]], [[Linkin Park]], [[Machine Head (band)|Machine Head]], [[Marilyn Manson]], [[Metallica]], [[MIA.]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[The Offspring]], [[Opeth]], [[Periphery (band)|Periphery]], [[Shinedown]], [[Skrillex]], [[Soundgarden]], [[Tenacious D]], [[The Subways]], and [[Trivium (band)|Trivium]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/spielplan |title=Spielplan 2016 - Samstag - Rock am Ring 2016 |publisher=Rock-am-ring.com |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-im-park.com/spielplan |title=Spielplan 2016 - Samstag - Rock im Park 2016 |publisher=Rock-im-park.com |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Center Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 1\n!Saturday, 2\n!Sunday, 3\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Linkin Park]]'''<br />\n[[Soundgarden]] <br />\n[[Gossip (band)|Gossip]] <br />\n[[Kasabian]] <br />\n[[Cypress Hill]] <br />\n[[The Subways]] <br />\n[[Tribes (band)|Tribes]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Metallica]]'''<br />\n[[Billy Talent]]<br />\n[[Tenacious D]]<br />\n[[Refused]]<br />\n[[Enter Shikari]]<br />\n[[Shinedown]] <br />\n[[Gojira (band)|Gojira]]<br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Die Toten Hosen]]'''<br />\n[[The Offspring]]<br />\n[[Dropkick Murphys]]<br />\n[[Dick Brave and the Backbeats|Dick Brave & The Backbeats]]<br />\n[[Donots]]<br />\n[[King Charles (musician)|King Charles]]<br />\n|}\n\n==2013 festival==\n2013's edition was sold out since the beginning of January, and included acts like [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[Green Day]], [[The Prodigy]], [[Fettes Brot]], [[Volbeat]], [[Stone Sour]], [[Sportfreunde Stiller]], [[Simple Plan]], [[The Killers]], [[Paramore]], [[All Time Low]], [[Fun.]], [[Imagine Dragons]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Korn]], [[Limp Bizkit]], [[Bullet for My Valentine]], [[Amon Amarth]], [[A Day to Remember]], [[Bring Me the Horizon]], [[Asking Alexandria]], [[The Bosshoss]], [[Airbourne (band)|Airbourne]], [[Bush (band)|Bush]], [[Hacktivist (band)|Hacktivist]], [[The Bloody Beetroots]], [[Hurts]], [[Phoenix (band)|Phoenix]], [[Tocotronic]], [[Biffy Clyro]], [[Stereophonics]], [[Kate Nash]], [[Selig (band)|Selig]], [[Bosse (band)|Bosse]], [[Kraftklub]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Royal Republic]], [[Seeed]], Casper, [[The Wombats]], [[ASAP Rocky]], [[Five Finger Death Punch]], [[Coheed And Cambria]], [[Coal Chamber]], [[Escape the Fate]], [[Newsted]] and [[Pierce the Veil]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Center Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 7\n!Saturday, 8\n!Sunday, 9\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Thirty Seconds to Mars]]'''<br />\n[[Fettes Brot]] <br />\n[[Cro (rapper)|Cro]] <br />\n[[Paramore]] <br />\n[[Fun.]] <br />\n[[Imagine Dragons]] <br />\n[[The Strypes]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n[[The Prodigy]]<br />\n'''[[Volbeat]]'''<br />\n[[Stone Sour]]<br />\n[[The Bosshoss]]<br />\n[[Airbourne (band)|Airbourne]] <br />\n[[Papa Roach]]<br />\n[[Hacktivist (band)|Hacktivist]]<br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Green Day]]'''<br />\n[[Sportfreunde Stiller]]<br />\n[[Kraftklub]]<br />\n[[Simple Plan]]<br />\n[[Bad Religion]]<br />\n[[Royal Republic]]<br />\n[[All Time Low]]<br />\n|}\n\n==2014 festival==\nThe 2014's edition of Rock am Ring was spread over 4 days.\nHeadliners: [[Iron Maiden]], [[Kings of Leon]], [[Linkin Park]], [[Metallica]] .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-2014-mit-vier-assen |title=Archived copy |accessdate=November 26, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131129102018/http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-2014-mit-vier-assen |archivedate=November 29, 2013 }}</ref> Other bands included [[Alligatoah]], [[Alter Bridge]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Babyshambles]], [[Booka Shade]], [[Die Fantastischen Vier]], [[Fall Out Boy]], [[Ghost (Swedish band)|Ghost]], [[Gogol Bordello]], [[Heaven Shall Burn]], [[In Extremo]], [[Jake Bugg]], [[Jan Delay & Disko No. 1]], [[John Newman (singer)|John Newman]], [[Karnivool]], [[Klangkarussell Live]], [[Kvelertak]], [[Left Boy]], [[Mando Diao]], [[Marteria]], [[Mastodon (band)|Mastodon]], [[Max\u00efmo Park]], [[Milky Chance]], [[Nine Inch Nails]], [[Of Mice & Men (band)|Of Mice & Men]], [[Opeth]], [[Portugal. The Man]], [[Queens of the Stone Age]], [[Rob Zombie]], [[Rudimental]], [[SDP (band)|SDP]], [[Sierra Kidd]], [[Slayer]], [[Suicide Silence]], [[Teesy]], [[Triggerfinger]], [[The Offspring]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-motivieren-die-fans |title=Archived copy |accessdate=December 12, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131214211050/http://www.rock-am-ring.com/news/ring-und-park-motivieren-die-fans |archivedate=December 14, 2013 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Center Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Thursday, 5\n!Friday, 6\n!Saturday, 7\n!Sunday, 8\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Iron Maiden]]'''<br />\n[[The Offspring]] <br />\n[[Pennywise (band)|Pennywise]] <br />\n[[Falling in Reverse]] <br />\n[[Klangkarussell]] <br />\n[[Rudimental]] <br />\n[[Cro (rapper)|Cro]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Kings Of Leon]]'''<br />\n[[Mando Diao]] <br />\n[[Kasabian]] <br />\n[[Rea Garvey]] <br />\n[[Jake Bugg]] <br />\n[[John Newman (singer)|John Newman]] <br />\n[[Rival Sons]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Linkin Park]]'''<br />\n[[Die Fantastischen Vier]] <br />\n[[Fall Out Boy]] <br />\n[[Alligatoah]] <br />\n[[Kaiser Chiefs]] <br />\n[[The Pretty Reckless]] <br />\n[[257ers]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Metallica]]'''<br />\n[[Avenged Sevenfold]] <br />\n[[Alter Bridge]] <br />\n[[In Extremo]] <br />\n[[Trivium (band)|Trivium]] <br />\n[[Black Stone Cherry]] <br />\n|}\n\n==2015 festival==\nIn 2015 the festival moved to a new location, [[Mendig Air Base]] \nHeadliners: [[Foo Fighters]], [[Die Toten Hosen]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Motionless in White]].<ref name=\"rock-am-ring.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rock-am-ring.com/2015/bands |title=Lineup 2016 - Rock am Ring 2016 |publisher=Rock-am-ring.com |date= |accessdate=2016-06-04}}</ref> Other bands included [[A Day to Remember]], [[Asking Alexandria]], [[Bad Religion]], [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]], [[Body Count (band)|Body Count]] Feat. [[Ice-T]], [[Eagles of Death Metal]], [[Enter Shikari]], [[Godsmack]], [[Hollywood Undead]], [[In Flames]], [[Interpol (band)|Interpol]], [[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]], [[Marilyn Manson]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], [[Papa Roach]], [[Parkway Drive]], [[Pop Evil]], [[Rise Against]], [[Royal Republic]], [[Skindred]], [[Slash (musician)|Slash]], [[Three Days Grace]], [[Yellowcard]] and [[Zebrahead]].<ref name=\"rock-am-ring.com\"/>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Volcano Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 5\n!Saturday, 6\n!Sunday, 7\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Die Toten Hosen]]''' <br />\n[[Rise Against]] <br />\n[[Broilers (band)|Broilers]] <br />\n[[A Day to Remember]]'''<br />\n[[Bad Religion]] <br />\n[[Yellowcard]] <br />\n[[Donots]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[The Prodigy]]'''<br />\n[[Kraftklub]] <br />\n[[Slash Feat. Myles Kennedy]] <br />\n[[Interpol (band)|Interpol]] <br />\n[[Royal Republic]] <br />\n[[Zebrahead]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Foo Fighters]]'''<br />\n[[Beatsteaks]] <br />\n[[Bastille (band)|Bastille]] <br />\n[[Frank Turner]] <br />\n[[Eagles of Death Metal]] <br />\n[[Ruen Brothers]]<br />\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''Crater Stage (Rock am Ring)'''\n|-\n!Friday, 5\n!Saturday, 6\n!Sunday, 7\n|-\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n[[Fritz Kalkbrenner]] <br />\n[[Marilyn Manson]] <br />\n[[Clueso]] <br />\n[[Tocotronic]]'''<br />\n[[Mighty Oaks (band)|Mighty Oaks]] <br />\n[[Jamie T]] <br />\n[[Ms Mr]] <br />\n[[T\u00fcsn]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n[[Marsimoto]] <br />\n[[Deichkind]] <br />\n[[K.I.Z]] <br />\n[[Prinz Pi]] <br />\n[[Trailerpark]] <br />\n[[Bilderbuch]] <br />\n[[Feine Sahne Fischfilet]] <br />\n[[Antilopen Gang]] <br />\n[[Zugezogen Maskulin]] <br />\n[[Sondaschule]] <br />\n|  style=\"text-align:center; vertical-align:top; width:200px;\"|\n'''[[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]'''<br />\n[[Mot\u00f6rhead]] <br />\n[[In Flames]] <br />\n[[Parkway Drive]] <br />\n[[Lamb of God (band)|Lamb of God]] <br />\n[[Papa Roach]] <br />\n[[Godsmack]] <br />\n|}\n\n==2016 festival==\nThe festival was cancelled during the second day due to severe thunderstorms.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.welt.de/vermischtes/article155967447/Festival-Rock-am-Ring-wird-endgueltig-abgebrochen.html | title= Festival \"Rock am Ring\" wird endg\u00fcltig abgebrochen}}</ref>\n\n==2017 festival==\nIn 2017 the festival returned to the [[N\u00fcrburgring]].\nHeadliners: [[Rammstein]], [[Die Toten Hosen]] and [[System of a Down]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rock-am-ring.com/history/2017|title=History - Rock am Ring 2017|website=Rock am Ring}}</ref>\n\nOn the evening of 2 June 2017, the first day of the festival, the sold out event with about 85,000 visitors was interrupted at 9:00 pm during a performance by the [[D\u00fcsseldorf]] band [[Broilers (band)|Broilers]] and the festival grounds cleared. The reason given was a terrorist situation. Other scheduled performances for Friday evening, including those of the headliner [[Rammstein]] and the rapper [[Marteria]], were cancelled.<ref>[http://www.sueddeutsche.de/panorama/festival-in-der-eifel-musikfestival-rock-am-ring-vorlaeufig-unterbrochen-1.3533703 ''Musikfestival \u201eRock am Ring\u201c vorl\u00e4ufig unterbrochen.''], ''Sueddeutsche.de''. 2 June 2017</ref> Three men were arrested and checked in [[Hesse]] that same evening. Two of the men assigned to the [[Salafist]] scene in Hesse had access rights in the form of bracelets, which gave them direct access to many festival areas. One of the men was also suspected of having links to the terrorist scene. However, on the morning of 3 June, after a search of the grounds and a raid of the suspect's homes, the police announced that the suspicion of a threatening attack had not been substantiated, so that the festival could continue on Saturday noon. The access rights to the festival site had been received by the two main suspects due to a short-term staffing request from an external security service provider.<ref>[http://www.faz.net/aktuell/gesellschaft/kriminalitaet/verkehrskontrolle-fuehrte-zu-rock-am-ring-abbruch-15048628.html ''Verkehrskontrolle f\u00fchrte zu \u201eRock am Ring\u201c-Abbruch.''], ''faz.net'', 6 June 2017</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Die Hintergr\u00fcnde zum Terroralarm bei Rock am Ring|periodical=Spiegel Online|url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/justiz/rock-am-ring-warum-es-einen-terror-alarm-gab-die-rekonstruktion-a-1150997.html|accessdate=2017-06-07|last=J\u00f6rg Diehl|date=2017-06-07}}</ref>\n\n==2018 festival==\nThe 2018 festival took place again in N\u00fcrburgring. Headliners: [[Thirty Seconds to Mars]], [[Muse (band)|Muse]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Avenged Sevenfold]], [[Marilyn Manson]], and [[Gorillaz]].<ref>[http://www.rock-am-ring.com/history/2018 2018]. ''Rock am Ring'' (official website). Retrieved 4 June 2018.</ref>\n\n==2019 festival==\nThe 2019 festival took place once again in N\u00fcrburgring. Headliners:[[Tool (band)| Tool]], [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]], [[Die \u00c4rzte|Die \u00c4rzte,]] and [[Slayer (band)|Slayer]].<ref>https://www.rock-am-ring.com/history/2019</ref> Out of the 77 artists in the lineup, 36 percent were rock bands, equally representing alternative rock, hard rock, and indie rock, and 29 percent were metal bands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.viberate.com/article/how-rock-are-you-the-best-festivals-for-headbangers/|title=How Rock Are You? The Best Festivals for Headbangers|last=Klancnik|first=Urban|date=10 December 2019|website=Viberate|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n{{Update section|date=June 2018}}\n<gallery>\nFile:Rock am Ring 2006.jpg|Rock am Ring 2006 stage, Dir en grey shown\nFile:Rock am ring 2007 mainstage.jpg|Rock am Ring 2007 main stage, 30 Seconds to Mars\nFile:20080606 rock im park alternative stage panorama.jpg|Panorama from the Alternative Stage in Rock Im Park 2008 festival.\nFile:20080608 rockimpark zeppelinfield panorama.jpg|Panorama from the Zeppelin Field Main Stage during the Rock Im Park 2008 event.\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category|Rock am Ring}}\n{{commons category|Rock im Park}}\n* [http://www.rock-am-ring.com Official Rock am Ring site]\n* [http://www.rock-im-park.com Official Rock im Park site]\n* [http://www.ringrocker.com Ringrocker.com]\n* [http://www.parkrocker.net Parkrocker.net]\n* [http://www.rockpalast.de/konzerte/2007/rock_am_ring/ Rockpalast \u2013 Rock am Ring 2007]\n* [http://www.newmixes.com/live_at_rock_am_ring-0601-0603-dab-2007.html Rock am Ring live sets audio files archive, Rockpalast broadcast]\n\n{{Rock festival}}\n\n[[Category:Heavy metal festivals in Germany]]\n[[Category:Concert tours]]\n[[Category:Music festivals established in 1985]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromRage Against The MachinetoRage Against the Machineusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rock_am_Ring_and_Rock_im_Park"}
{"title_page": "Fort De La Boulaye Site", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Fort De La Boulaye\n  | nrhp_type =nhl\n  | image = Fort de La Boulaye.jpg\n  | caption = Location of Fort de la Boulaye\n  | nearest_city= [[Phoenix, Louisiana|Phoenix]], [[Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana|Plaquemines Parish]], [[Louisiana]], U.S.A.\n  | coordinates = {{coord|29|38|57|N|89|56|40|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Louisiana#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1699&ndash;1700\n| architect= Unknown\n| architecture= \n| designated_nrhp_type= October 9, 1960<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=259&ResourceType=Site|title=Fort De La Boulaye|accessdate=2008-01-28|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308014121/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=259&ResourceType=Site|archive-date=2011-03-08|url-status=dead}} ''<--Dead link, November 2015.''</ref>\n | added = October 15, 1966\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=66000378\n}}\n'''Fort De La Boulaye Site''', also known as '''Fort Mississippi,''' is the site of a fort built by the French in 1699&ndash;1700, to support their claim of the Mississippi River and valley. Native Americans forced the French to vacate the fort by 1707.\n\nThe site was declared a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1960, as part of the history of French colonization of the area. The state of Louisiana had earlier erected an historical marker, with the following text:\n''FORT de la BOULAYE  First white settlement in present-day Louisiana, erected by Bienville in 1699 on this spot (then the bank of the Mississippi), prevented Britain's seizure of the Mississippi Valley.''<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{NHLS url|id=66000378|title=''Accompanying photos from 1958, 1969, and 1976.''|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(999&nbsp;KB)}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1698, [[Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville]], and his brothers, [[Jean-Baptiste Le Moyne de Bienville]] and [[Antoine Le Moyne de Ch\u00e2teauguay]], participated in an expedition to rediscover the [[River mouth|mouth]] of the [[Mississippi River]]. It could be difficult to find among the many competing [[bayou]]s and waterways.\n\nIn 1699, they founded '''Fort Mississippi''' on a ridge a little more than one kilometer from the shore of the river, on the east bank, and about twenty kilometers south of the future city of [[New Orleans]].  The fort was completed in 1700. It was built in [[stockade]] wood and defended by [[artillery|six guns]], in order to protect the region from attacks and incursions by the [[British North America|English]] and [[New Spain|Spanish]]. The fort was renamed '''''Fort de la Boulaye''''' and was commanded by [[Louis Juchereau de St. Denis]].\n\nIn 1707, the [[Caddo]]an tribe, hostile to the presence of encroaching soldiers, forced them to abandon the fort and to go to the French settlement of [[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]].  Only the officer Juchereau de St. Denis, friend of the Caddo, was permitted to continue living in the fort. [[Garrison]]s of French troops occasionally visited the site. In 1714, Juchereau de St. Denis was assigned to lead a new expedition, with the objective of defending the western boundaries of [[Louisiana (New France)]]. He established '''''[[Fort des Natchitoches]]'''''.\n\nBy the middle of the 18th century Fort de la Boulaye was abandoned. [[Tropical storm]]s eventually destroyed this fort.\n\nIn the 20th century [[archaeology|archaeologists]] conducted surveys and located the site of fort; they found remnants of [[palisade]] and building logs, burned poles, and evidence of a cannonball. The site has been designated a [[National Historic Landmark]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[La Balize, Louisiana|Fort de la Balize]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana]]\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Louisiana]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links== \n*[http://hnoc.minisisinc.com/thnoc/catalog/3/243 Fort De La Boulaye Collection] at [http://www.hnoc.org The Historic New Orleans Collection] \n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Forts in Louisiana|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:Colonial forts in Louisiana|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:French forts in the United States|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:French-American culture in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Forts on the National Register of Historic Places in Louisiana|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:1700 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Fort De La Boulaye\n  | nrhp_type =nhl\n  | image = Fort de La Boulaye.jpg\n  | caption = Location of Fort de la Boulaye\n  | nearest_city= [[Phoenix, Louisiana|Phoenix]], [[Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana|Plaquemines Parish]], [[Louisiana]], U.S.A.\n  | coordinates = {{coord|29|38|57|N|89|56|40|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin = Louisiana#USA\n  | area =\n  | built =1699&ndash;1700\n| architect= Unknown\n| architecture= \n| designated_nrhp_type= October 9, 1960<ref name=\"nhlsum\">{{cite web|url=http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=259&ResourceType=Site|title=Fort De La Boulaye|accessdate=2008-01-28|work=National Historic Landmark summary listing|publisher=National Park Service|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110308014121/http://tps.cr.nps.gov/nhl/detail.cfm?ResourceId=259&ResourceType=Site|archive-date=2011-03-08|url-status=dead}} ''<--Dead link, November 2015.''</ref>\n | added = October 15, 1966\n | governing_body = Private\n | refnum=66000378\n}}\n'''Fort De La Boulaye Site''', also known as '''Fort Mississippi,''' is the site of a fort built by the French in 1699&ndash;1700, to support their claim of the Mississippi River and valley. Native Americans forced the French to vacate the fort by 1707.\n\nThe site was declared a [[National Historic Landmark]] in 1960, as part of the history of French colonization of the area. The state of Louisiana had earlier erected an historical marker, with the following text:\n''FORT de la BOULAYE  First white settlement in present-day Louisiana, erected by Bienville in 1699 on this spot (then the bank of the Mississippi), prevented Britain's seizure of the Mississippi Valley.''<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{NHLS url|id=66000378|title=''Accompanying photos from 1958, 1969, and 1976.''|photos=y}}&nbsp;{{small|(999&nbsp;KB)}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1698, [[Pierre Le Moyne d'Iberville]], and his brothers, [[Jean-Baptiste Le Moyne de Bienville]] and [[Antoine Le Moyne de Ch\u00e2teauguay]], participated in an expedition to rediscover the [[River mouth|mouth]] of the [[Mississippi River]]. It could be difficult to find among the many competing [[bayou]]s and waterways.\n\nIn 1699, they founded '''Fort Mississippi''' on a ridge a little more than one kilometer from the shore of the river, on the east bank, and about twenty kilometers south of the future city of [[New Orleans]].  The fort was completed in 1700. It was built in [[stockade]] wood and defended by [[artillery|six guns]], in order to protect the region from attacks and incursions by the [[British North America|English]] and [[New Spain|Spanish]]. The fort was renamed '''''Fort de la Boulaye''''' and was commanded by [[Louis Juchereau de St. Denis]].\n\nIn 1707, the [[Caddo]]an tribe, hostile to the presence of encroaching soldiers, forced them to abandon the fort and to go to the French settlement of [[Biloxi, Mississippi|Biloxi]].  Only the officer Juchereau de St. Denis, friend of the Caddo, was permitted to continue living in the fort. [[Garrison]]s of French troops occasionally visited the site. In 1714, Juchereau de St. Denis was assigned to lead a new expedition, with the objective of defending the western boundaries of [[Louisiana (New France)]]. He established '''''[[Fort des Natchitoches]]'''''.\n\nBy the middle of the 18th century Fort de la Boulaye was abandoned. [[Tropical storm]]s eventually destroyed this fort.\n\nIn the 20th century [[archaeology|archaeologists]] conducted surveys and located the site of fort; they found remnants of [[palisade]] and building logs, burned poles, and evidence of a cannonball. The site has been designated a [[National Historic Landmark]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[La Balize, Louisiana|Fort de la Balize]]\n*[[National Register of Historic Places listings in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana]]\n*[[List of National Historic Landmarks in Louisiana]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places}}\n\n[[Category:National Historic Landmarks in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Forts in Louisiana|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:Colonial forts in Louisiana|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:French forts in the United States|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:French-American culture in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Forts on the National Register of Historic Places in Louisiana|De La Boulaye]]\n[[Category:1700 establishments in the French colonial empire]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Plaquemines Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "Roxguidry", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added link to archive catalog", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fort_De_La_Boulaye_Site"}
{"title_page": "The Level, Brighton", "text_new": "{{short description|Park in Brighton, UK}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = The Level\n| photo = File:The Level, Brighton (Northeastward View from opposite Oxford Street) (November 2015) (1).JPG\n| photo_width = \n| photo_caption = The northern half of the Level\n| map = \n| map_width = \n| type = Public Park\n| location = [[Brighton]], England\n| lat_d = \n| long_d = \n| source = \n| coords = {{Coord|50.8305|-0.1327|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| area = 8 acres\n| created = 1822\n| awards           = [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]], [[Green Flag Award]], National Landscape award, [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]], Sussex Heritage Trust\n| parking          = \n| publictransit    = \n| transport        = [[National Cycle Route 20]], Buses: 21, 22, 24, 25, 26, 37, 37B, 38, 46, 48, 49, 50 and 81<ref name=\"BHCC\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |website=Brighton & Hove City Council |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222706/https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n| operator = [[Brighton and Hove|Brighton & Hove City Council]]\n| status = Open year round\n| open = 24 hours\n}}\n'''The Level''' is an [[urban park]] in central [[Brighton]], on the south coast of the [[United Kingdom]]. The park is a triangle of 8 acres bounded by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace (A270) to the east and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west. In the past, the land has been used as a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] for the [[Prince of Wales]] and as a setting for huge dinner parties to commemorate events such as the defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] and the coronation of [[Queen Victoria]].\n\nPresent day features of the Level include a grassed area with [[elm trees]] and outdoor seating, several caf\u00e9s, a [[skatepark]], a rose garden, a children's [[playground]] and a pond. The park was substantially redeveloped in the early 2010s.\n\n== Overview == \nThe Level is located in central Brighton, about {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of the seafront.<ref name=\"Fines45\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=45.}}</ref>  It now covers {{convert|8.05|acre|ha}} but was originally much larger, encompassing the present-day Victoria Gardens and Valley Gardens to the south and the land now occupied by [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] to the north.<ref name=\"NEB176\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=176.}}</ref>  It forms a rough triangle enclosed by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace and Richmond Place (A270) to the east{{#tag:ref|Originally the southernmost part of Lewes Road.<ref name=\"Clunn152\"/>|group=note}} and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west.<ref name=\"Clunn152\">{{Harvnb|Clunn|1953|p=152.}}</ref>\n\nThe park is surrounded by [[elm trees]] and is laid out in three sections.  The northern part of the [[urban park]] is a grassed area. In the middle section is a [[skatepark]]. The southern part of the park is a children's [[playground]] and also includes two cafes, public lavatories, a pavilion which can be hired for community use, a pond with a fountain, a sensory garden and a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]].<ref name=\"BHCC\" /><ref name=\"LUC\" />\n\n[[Brighton and Hove City Council]] added The Level to their Local List of Heritage Assets in 2015.  The council's assessment described it as \"[a] well-designed municipal public playground, within an early public park ... [which] contributes greatly to the character of the area\".<ref name=\"LLHA-D\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|title=Local List of Heritage Assets: D|year=2014|publisher=[[Brighton and Hove City Council]]|format=PDF|accessdate=24 March 2020|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gWQ8qmII?url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|archivedate=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Formation and history ==\n[[File:The Level, a park in central Brighton, UK.png|thumb|right|250px|This map shows the bounds of the Level and nearby features]]\n[[File:The_Level,_west_side.jpg|thumb|right|250px|West side of the Level with elm trees, 2006]]\n<!-- The Level was mentioned in 1779 as grassland outside a farmhouse, which stood where the [[King and Queen, Brighton|King and Queen]] pub stands now across from Victoria Gardens. The area was much larger than the park today, extending from Victoria Gardens to the north, over the present site and into what is now [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]].<ref name=\"Bance\"/> -->\n\nLondon Road and Lewes Road, two major routes leading out of Brighton, were built along steep-sided valleys through which [[Winterbourne (stream)|winterbournes]] flowed intermittently.  The valleys, and therefore the streams, met where The Level is now and flowed out to sea at [[Old Steine|the Steine]].<ref name=\"Antram4\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=4.}}</ref>  The land was always marshy and swampy and was never built upon.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>  Instead, it became a popular place for public recreation and entertainment as Brighton grew into a fashionable resort town in the 18th century.<ref name=\"Fines25\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=25.}}</ref>  After the town's authorities banned ball games and other traditional entertainments on [[Old Steine|the Steine]] in 1787, The Level became the focus for the early resort's sporting activities:<ref name=\"Seldon62\">{{Harvnb|Seldon|2002|p=62.}}</ref> four years later the Prince of Wales (later [[George IV of the United Kingdom]]) laid out a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] on the northern side.  The [[Prince of Wales Ground]] hosted early [[First-class cricket|first-class]] matches and served as the home of [[Brighton Cricket Club]], one of the principal founders of [[Sussex County Cricket Club]] 50 years later.  In 1822 the cricket ground moved to a nearby site called the Hanover Ground; after another move to the [[Royal Brunswick Ground]] on the [[Brunswick (Hove)|Brunswick estate]], it was established on its present site on Eaton Road in Hove in 1872.<ref name=\"Seldon62\"/>  The Bat and Ball pub on Ditchling Road, facing the west side of The Level, commemorates the ground.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>  Other popular events included the town's annual bonfire celebrations on [[Guy Fawkes Night]], regular circuses and fairs, and traditional activities such as [[bat and trap]]<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> and skipping.  Writing in 1883, a contributor to the ''[[Sussex Archaeological Society|Sussex Archaeological Collections]]'' journal noted that the local [[Good Friday]] tradition of skipping was still maintained at The Level, where \"scores of skippers\" could be seen.<ref name=\"Underwood24\">{{Harvnb|Underwood|1978|p=24.}}</ref>\n\nAs well as these informal recreational events, The Level (especially the southern part, closest to the town centre) was used for formal, town-wide events and commemorations, such as the Prince's birthday celebrations.<ref name=\"Fines25\"/>  The [[War of the Sixth Coalition|Allied Powers']] defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] was celebrated in Brighton by the Great Peace Festival of August 1814.  A mass dinner of roast beef and plum puddings was served at 75 double rows of tables for more than 7,000 people,<ref name=\"Fines26\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=26.}}</ref><ref name=\"Erredge299-300\">{{Harvnb|Erredge|1862|pp=299\u2013300.}}</ref> and the town's authorities organised activities such as running races, [[stoolball]], dancing and \"kiss-in-the-ring\".<ref name=\"Fines26\"/>  The coronations of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] and [[Queen Victoria]] and the end of both the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and the [[Crimean War]] were celebrated with similar large-scale public feasts.<ref name=\"NEB177\"/>\n\nOn 22 April 1822, the 8 acres of land that nowadays form The Level was given in trust to Brighton by [[Thomas Read Kemp]] and other landowners.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=184.}}</ref>  Thereafter, apart from {{convert|105|acre|ha}} of [[downland]] near [[Brighton Racecourse]], far out of town on top of Race Hill, The Level was the only area of common land available to the town's residents.<ref name=\"OOB50\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=50.}}</ref>  In the same year Union Road was built to connect the Ditchling and Lewes Roads, marking the northern edge of The Level, and the land to the north of it was sold.  Local entrepreneur James Ireland established the Royal Gardens on this section, but the venture failed and the land was later sold again; [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] was built on it from 1849.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\"/>  Also in 1822 The Level itself was designed and laid out by architect [[Amon Henry Wilds]] and horticulturist [[Henry Phillips (horticulturist)|Henry Phillips]].<ref name=\"Antram184\"/>  The elm trees, a gift to the town from the [[Henry Pelham, 3rd Earl of Chichester]], were planted in November 1844.<ref name=\"Dale217\">{{Harvnb|Dale|1976|p=217.}}</ref>  Many were uprooted in the [[Great Storm of 1987]],<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> although at the time Brighton Borough Council was considering felling many of them because of an outbreak of [[Dutch elm disease]].<ref name=\"Trimingham43\">{{Harvnb|Trimingham|1999|p=43.}}</ref>\n\nBy the time [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]] became Queen in 1837, The Level was an important part of the growing resort of Brighton: the town extended for {{convert|1|mi|km}} northwards from the seafront, encompassing a \"splendid boulevard\" formed by the green spaces of [[Old Steine]], Valley Gardens (with [[St Peter's Church, Brighton|St Peter's Church]] as the centrepiece) and The Level itself.<ref name=\"Fines45\"/>  Also at this time, when the success of [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway|Britain's first inter-city railway]] encouraged investment and speculation in the new form of transport, six routes were suggested for a railway line between London and Brighton.  The shortest and most direct, covering {{convert|47.5|mi|km}} but requiring the most expensive construction work, would have terminated just north of The Level on the site of James Ireland's pleasure gardens.<ref name=\"OOB133\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=133.}}</ref>  After [[Brighton main line|a line]] was built slightly further west in 1841, Brighton's population grew rapidly and its character changed.<ref name=\"NEB268\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=268.}}</ref>  One feature of the mid- to late 19th century was a rapid growth in prostitution; it was common at The Level, when at night \"the scenes ... were said to beggar all description\".<ref name=\"OOB196\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=196.}}</ref>  A police station was established in a small building at the southern end of the park in 1865.  In 1919 it became the headquarters of the Brighton Parks and Gardens Department, and was later converted into a caf\u00e9.<ref name=\"NEB177\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=177.}}</ref>\n\nPolitical gatherings were also a feature of The Level.  Among the regular events held there was the annual May Day rally and demonstration by the Brighton Trades Council, which was formed in 1890.  These events \"became well known nationally\"; members included [[Margaret Bondfield]], who was employed as a draper's assistant in Brighton at the time and who later became the first female [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet minister in the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Fines78\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=78.}}</ref>  Later, local resident [[Harry Cowley]] was an organiser of the barrow boys\u2014many of whom had been in the armed forces during World War I\u2014on nearby Oxford Street.  In the early 1920s he negotiated permission for them to sell fruit and vegetables alongside the rose garden on The Level. This went on until the Open Market was built on the opposite side of Ditchling Road in 1926, when the boys moved there instead.<ref name=\"NEB194\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=194.}}</ref><ref name=\"OpenMarket\">{{cite web |title=The History of Brighton Open Market |url=http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |website=Open Market |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322142700/http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the 1930s, Cowley and his associates broke up a meeting of the Fascist League at The Level.<ref name=\"Cowley\">{{cite web |title=WW2 People's War - Harry Cowley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510054150/http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |archive-date=10 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There was again a clash with fascists in June 1948, when members of the [[43 Group]] and Brighton locals prevented a meeting of [[Oswald Mosley]]'s [[British Union of Fascists]]. What became known as the Battle of the Level ensured no fascists returned to Brighton until the 1960s.<ref name=\"Bance\">{{cite news |last1=Bance |first1=M. |title=Brighton Level History |url=http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Post Magazine |date=1 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321231149/http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Greenstein\">{{cite book |last1=Greenstein |first1=Tony |title=Fighting Fascism in Brighton and the South Coast |date=2011 |publisher=Brighton History Workshop |location=Brighton}}</ref>\n\nThe children's [[playground]] was first constructed in 1927 by Bertie Hubbard MacLaren (Superintendent of Parks and Gardens).<ref name=\"Captain\">{{cite web |title=Captain Bertie Hubbard MacClaren |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225924/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He added a boating pond and a [[pergola]].  The pond has since been made smaller.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>  During World War II, the [[Royal Engineers]] [[Eminent domain|requisitioned]] the [[Brighton Forum|Chichester Diocesan Training College for Schoolmistresses at Ditchling Road]];<ref name=\"NEB130\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=130.}}</ref> they put up several [[Nissen hut]]s on The Level to give them more space, and these temporary buildings stayed until well into the 1950s.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>\n\n== Recent history ==\n\n===Peace camp===\nBrighton Women's Peace Camp was set up on the Level on 15 February 1983, in support of the [[Greenham Common Women's Peace Camp]]. At [[RAF Greenham Common]], women were protesting against [[cruise missile]]s from the USA being placed on British soil. The Brighton camp was one of many short-lived satellite camps that appeared around the United Kingdom in early 1983.<ref name=\"PC\">{{cite journal |last1=Carroll |first1=Sam |title=Brighton Womens Peace Camp, 1983: Second Wave Feminism and the Womens Peace Movement. |journal=University of Sussex Journal of Contemporary History |date=2005 |volume=8 |issue=Winter |url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134637/http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast to the heavy-handed treatment of campers at Greenham by the authorities, Brighton participants said \"The Brighton Corporation have been very good. And the police have been very good.\"\n<ref name=\"Wimmin\">{{cite news |last1=Davie |first1=Michael |title=Who's afraid of wimmin? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=5 September 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134844/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===BUFF===\nThe Brighton Urban Free Festival (BUFF) was held on the Level for the first time on September 1, 1984. It was a free music festival which aimed to promote local bands. It occurred again in 1985, then moved to [[Preston Park, Brighton|Preston Park]] in 1986, before returning to the Level in 1987, 1988, 1991 and 1992. Bands which played included [[Peter and the Test Tube Babies]], [[These Animal Men]] and [[Levellers (band)|The Levellers]].<ref name=\"BUFF\">{{cite web |title=Music and performance |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225913/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Skate park ==\n[[File:Brighton,_Skate_Park_(31840008245).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The redeveloped skate park]]\nThe first [[skatepark]] was designed by architects Murrin and Partners and built on the Level in 1978. There was a nearby skateshop called Pig City and in the 1990s there were regular skate competitions.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\">{{cite news |last1=Team |first1=Timeout |title=LOCAL HISTORY: The Level Skatepark in the 1980s |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Argus |date=16 August 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321224649/https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the early 2000s, an [[elm tree]] next to the skate park became famous for having many shoes thrown into its branches. It then had to be felled in 2018 after catching [[Dutch elm disease]] from elms on the other side of the cycle path.<ref name=\"ShoeTree\">{{cite news |last1=Wadsworth |first1=Jo |title=Level skatepark\u2019s shoe tree to be felled after succumbing to elm disease |url=https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Brighton and Hove News |date=5 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322124923/https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe council received a lottery grant of \u00a32.2 million to build a new park, which was designed by Freestyle. The new park opened in June 2013.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\" />\n\n== Redevelopment ==\nFollowing a successful [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]] grant request, the Level was substantially redeveloped from 2009 onwards, expanding MacLaren's original design: the skate park was moved and rebuilt, taking up what had previously been a grassed area; the pavilions were regenerated; the model boating pond was restored with a fountain; the playground was reconfigured; a sensory garden was added; a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]] was provided.<ref name=\"LUC\">{{cite web |title=LUC picks up Sussex Heritage Trust award for The Level in Brighton |url=https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |website=LUC - Environmental Planning, Design and Management |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=13 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222655/https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"LI\">{{cite web |title=Enhancing Brighton\u2019s Level |url=https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |website=Landscape Institute |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161234/https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe park won a Sussex Heritage Trust award in 2016 and is now [[Green Flag Award]] accreditated.<ref name=\"LUC\" /> It also won a [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]] and National Landscape award.<ref name=\"CTA\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |website=Civic Trust Awards |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161233/https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NLA\">{{cite web |title=National accolade for The Level restoration |url=https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |website=new.brighton-hove.gov.uk |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161508/https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Antram|first=Nicholas|last2=Morrice|first2=Richard|title=Brighton and Hove|series=Pevsner Architectural Guides|publisher=Yale University Press|location=London|year=2008|isbn=978-0-300-12661-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clunn|first=Harold P.|authorlink=Harold Clunn|title=The Capital-by-the-Sea|year=1953|publisher=The Southern Publishing Co Ltd|location=Brighton|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Collis|first=Rose|others=(based on the original by Tim Carder)|title=The New Encyclopaedia of Brighton|edition=1st|year=2010|publisher=Brighton & Hove Libraries|location=Brighton|isbn=978-0-9564664-0-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Erredge|first=John Ackerson|title=History of Brighthelmston, or Brighton as I view it and others knew it|year=1862|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=uK8HAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=29 March 2020|language=en|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Dale|first=Antony|title=Brighton Town and Brighton People|publisher=Phillimore & Co. Ltd|location=Chichester|year=1976|isbn=0-85033-219-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Fines|first=Ken|title=A History of Brighton & Hove|publisher=Phillimore & Co|location=Chichester|year=2002|isbn=1-86077-231-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gilbert|first=Edmund M.|title=Brighton: Old Ocean's Bauble|year=1975|origyear=1954|publisher=Flare Books|location=Hassocks|isbn=0-901759-39-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Seldon|first=Anthony|authorlink=Anthony Seldon|title=Brave New City: Brighton & Hove Past, Present, Future|publisher=Pomegranate Press|location=Lewes|year=2002|isbn=0-9542587-1-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Trimingham|first=Adam|title=Trimingham's Brighton|publisher=Pomegranate Press|location=Westmeston|year=1999|isbn=0-9533493-2-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Underwood|first=Eric|title=Brighton|year=1978|publisher=B.T. Batsford Ltd|location=London|isbn=0-7134-0895-2|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|The Level, Brighton}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-sussex-25005565 BBC history of the Level in pictures]\n\n{{Brighton and Hove}}\n\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Brighton and Hove]]\n[[Category:1822 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Park in Brighton, UK}}\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = The Level\n| photo = File:The Level, Brighton (Northeastward View from opposite Oxford Street) (November 2015) (1).JPG\n| photo_width = \n| photo_caption = The northern half of the Level\n| map = \n| map_width = \n| type = Public Park\n| location = [[Brighton]], England\n| lat_d = \n| long_d = \n| source = \n| coords = {{Coord|50.8305|-0.1327|type:landmark_region:GB|display=inline,title}}\n| area = 8 acres\n| created = 1822\n| awards           = [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]], [[Green Flag Award]], National Landscape award, [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]], Sussex Heritage Trust\n| parking          = \n| publictransit    = \n| transport        = [[National Cycle Route 20]], Buses: 21, 22, 24, 25, 26, 37, 37B, 38, 46, 48, 49, 50 and 81<ref name=\"BHCC\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |website=Brighton & Hove City Council |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222706/https://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/content/leisure-and-libraries/parks-and-green-spaces/level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n| operator = [[Brighton and Hove|Brighton & Hove City Council]]\n| status = Open year round\n| open = 24 hours\n}}\n'''The Level''' is an [[urban park]] in central [[Brighton]], on the south coast of the [[United Kingdom]]. The park is a triangle of 8 acres bounded by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace (A270) to the east and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west. In the past, the land has been used as a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] for the [[Prince of Wales]] and as a setting for huge dinner parties to commemorate events such as the defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] and the coronation of [[Queen Victoria]].\n\nPresent day features of the Level include a grassed area with [[elm trees]] and outdoor seating, several caf\u00e9s, a [[skatepark]], a rose garden, a childrens [[playground]] and a pond. The park was substantially redeveloped in the early 2010s.\n\n== Overview == \nThe Level is located in central Brighton, about {{convert|1|mi|km}} north of the seafront.<ref name=\"Fines45\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=45.}}</ref>  It now covers {{convert|8.05|acre|ha}} but was originally much larger, encompassing the present-day Victoria Gardens and Valley Gardens to the south and the land now occupied by [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] to the north.<ref name=\"NEB176\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=176.}}</ref>  It forms a rough triangle enclosed by Union Street to the north, Richmond Terrace and Richmond Place (A270) to the east{{#tag:ref|Originally the southernmost part of Lewes Road.<ref name=\"Clunn152\"/>|group=note}} and Ditchling Road ([[A23 road|A23]]) to the west.<ref name=\"Clunn152\">{{Harvnb|Clunn|1953|p=152.}}</ref>\n\nThe park is surrounded by [[elm trees]] and is laid out in three sections.  The northern part of the [[urban park]] is a grassed area. In the middle section is a [[skatepark]]. The southern part of the park is a children's [[playground]] and also includes two cafes, public lavatories, a pavilion which can be hired for community use, a pond with a fountain, a sensory garden and a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]].<ref name=\"BHCC\" /><ref name=\"LUC\" />\n\n[[Brighton and Hove City Council]] added The Level to their Local List of Heritage Assets in 2015.  The council's assessment described it as \"[a] well-designed municipal public playground, within an early public park ... [which] contributes greatly to the character of the area\".<ref name=\"LLHA-D\">{{cite web|url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|title=Local List of Heritage Assets: D|year=2014|publisher=[[Brighton and Hove City Council]]|format=PDF|accessdate=24 March 2020|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6gWQ8qmII?url=http://www.brighton-hove.gov.uk/sites/brighton-hove.gov.uk/files/LLHA%20D.pdf|archivedate=4 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Formation and history ==\n[[File:The Level, a park in central Brighton, UK.png|thumb|right|250px|This map shows the bounds of the Level and nearby features]]\n[[File:The_Level,_west_side.jpg|thumb|right|250px|West side of the Level with elm trees, 2006]]\n<!-- The Level was mentioned in 1779 as grassland outside a farmhouse, which stood where the [[King and Queen, Brighton|King and Queen]] pub stands now across from Victoria Gardens. The area was much larger than the park today, extending from Victoria Gardens to the north, over the present site and into what is now [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]].<ref name=\"Bance\"/> -->\n\nLondon Road and Lewes Road, two major routes leading out of Brighton, were built along steep-sided valleys through which [[Winterbourne (stream)|winterbournes]] flowed intermittently.  The valleys, and therefore the streams, met where The Level is now and flowed out to sea at [[Old Steine|the Steine]].<ref name=\"Antram4\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=4.}}</ref>  The land was always marshy and swampy and was never built upon.<ref name=\"NEB176\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=176.}}</ref>  Instead, it became a popular place for public recreation and entertainment as Brighton grew into a fashionable resort town in the 18th century.<ref name=\"Fines25\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=25.}}</ref>  After the town's authorities banned ball games and other traditional entertainments on [[Old Steine|the Steine]] in 1787, The Level became the focus for the early resort's sporting activities:<ref name=\"Seldon62\">{{Harvnb|Seldon|2002|p=62.}}</ref> four years later the Prince of Wales (later [[George IV of the United Kingdom]]) laid out a [[Ground (cricket)|cricket ground]] on the northern side.  The [[Prince of Wales Ground]] hosted early [[First-class cricket|first-class]] matches and served as the home of [[Brighton Cricket Club]], one of the principal founders of [[Sussex County Cricket Club]] 50 years later.  In 1822 the cricket ground moved to a nearby site called the Hanover Ground; after another move to the [[Royal Brunswick Ground]] on the [[Brunswick (Hove)|Brunswick estate]], it was established on its present site on Eaton Road in Hove in 1872.<ref name=\"Seldon62\"/>  The Bat and Ball pub on Ditchling Road, facing the west side of The Level, commemorates the ground.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>  Other popular events included the town's annual bonfire celebrations on [[Guy Fawkes Night]], regular circuses and fairs, and traditional activities such as [[bat and trap]]<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> and skipping.  Writing in 1883, a contributor to the ''[[Sussex Archaeological Society|Sussex Archaeological Collections]]'' journal noted that the local [[Good Friday]] tradition of skipping was still maintained at The Level, where \"scores of skippers\" could be seen.<ref name=\"Underwood24\">{{Harvnb|Underwood|1978|p=24.}}</ref>\n\nAs well as these informal recreational events, The Level (especially the southern part, closest to the town centre) was used for formal, town-wide events and commemorations, such as the Prince's birthday celebrations.<ref name=\"Fines25\"/>  The [[War of the Sixth Coalition|Allied Powers']] defeat of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]] was celebrated in Brighton by the Great Peace Festival of August 1814.  A mass dinner of roast beef and plum puddings was served at 75 double rows of tables for more than 7,000 people,<ref name=\"Fines26\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=26.}}</ref><ref name=\"Erredge299-300\">{{Harvnb|Erredge|1862|pp=299\u2013300.}}</ref> and the town's authorities organised activities such as running races, [[stoolball]], dancing and \"kiss-in-the-ring\".<ref name=\"Fines26\"/>  The coronations of [[George IV of the United Kingdom|King George IV]] and [[Queen Victoria]] and the end of both the [[Napoleonic Wars]] and the [[Crimean War]] were celebrated with similar large-scale public feasts.<ref name=\"NEB177\"/>\n\nOn 22 April 1822, the 8 acres of land that nowadays form The Level was given in trust to Brighton by [[Thomas Read Kemp]] and other landowners.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\">{{Harvnb|Antram|Morrice|2008|p=184.}}</ref>  Thereafter, apart from {{convert|105|acre|ha}} of [[downland]] near [[Brighton Racecourse]], far out of town on top of Race Hill, The Level was the only area of common land available to the town's residents.<ref name=\"OOB50\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=50.}}</ref>  In the same year Union Road was built to connect the Ditchling and Lewes Roads, marking the northern edge of The Level, and the land to the north of it was sold.  Local entrepreneur James Ireland established the Royal Gardens on this section, but the venture failed and the land was later sold again; [[Park Crescent, Brighton|Park Crescent]] was built on it from 1849.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/><ref name=\"Antram184\"/>  Also in 1822 The Level itself was designed and laid out by architect [[Amon Henry Wilds]] and horticulturist [[Henry Phillips (horticulturist)|Henry Phillips]].<ref name=\"Antram184\"/>  The elm trees, a gift to the town from the [[Henry Pelham, 3rd Earl of Chichester]], were planted in November 1844.<ref name=\"Dale217\">{{Harvnb|Dale|1976|p=217.}}</ref>  Many were uprooted in the [[Great Storm of 1987]],<ref name=\"NEB176\"/> although at the time Brighton Borough Council was considering felling many of them because of an outbreak of [[Dutch elm disease]].<ref name=\"Trimingham43\">{{Harvnb|Trimingham|1999|p=43.}}</ref>\n\nBy the time [[Queen Victoria|Victoria]] became Queen in 1837, The Level was an important part of the growing resort of Brighton: the town extended for {{convert|1|mi|km}} northwards from the seafront, encompassing a \"splendid boulevard\" formed by the green spaces of [[Old Steine]], Valley Gardens (with [[St Peter's Church, Brighton|St Peter's Church]] as the centrepiece) and The Level itself.<ref name=\"Fines45\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=45.}}</ref>  Also at this time, when the success of [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway|Britain's first inter-city railway]] encouraged investment and speculation in the new form of transport, six routes were suggested for a railway line between London and Brighton.  The shortest and most direct, covering {{convert|47.5|mi|km}} but requiring the most expensive construction work, would have terminated just north of The Level on the site of James Ireland's pleasure gardens.<ref name=\"OOB133\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=133.}}</ref>  After [[Brighton main line|a line]] was built slightly further west in 1841, Brighton's population grew rapidly and its character changed.<ref name=\"NEB268\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=268.}}</ref>  One feature of the mid- to late 19th century was a rapid growth in prostitution; it was common at The Level, when at night \"the scenes ... were said to beggar all description\".<ref name=\"OOB196\">{{Harvnb|Gilbert|1975|p=196.}}</ref>  A police station was established in a small building at the southern end of the park in 1865.  In 1919 it became the headquarters of the Brighton Parks and Gardens Department, and was later converted into a caf\u00e9.<ref name=\"NEB177\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=177.}}</ref>\n\nPolitical gatherings were also a feature of The Level.  Among the regular events held there was the annual May Day rally and demonstration by the Brighton Trades Council, which was formed in 1890.  These events \"became well known nationally\"; members included [[Margaret Bondfield]], who was employed as a draper's assistant in Brighton at the time and who later became the first female [[Cabinet of the United Kingdom|cabinet minister in the United Kingdom]].<ref name=\"Fines78\">{{Harvnb|Fines|2002|p=78.}}</ref>  Later, local resident [[Harry Cowley]] was an organiser of the barrow boys\u2014many of whom had been in the armed forces during World War I\u2014on nearby Oxford Street.  In the early 1920s he negotiated permission for them to sell fruit and vegetables alongside the rose garden on The Level. This went on until the Open Market was built on the opposite side of Ditchling Road in 1926, when the boys moved there instead.<ref name=\"NEB194\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=194.}}</ref><ref name=\"OpenMarket\">{{cite web |title=The History of Brighton Open Market |url=http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |website=Open Market |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322142700/http://www.brightonopenmarket.co.uk/history-of-brighton-open-market/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the 1930s, Cowley and his associates broke up a meeting of the Fascist League at The Level.<ref name=\"Cowley\">{{cite web |title=WW2 People's War - Harry Cowley |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |website=BBC |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190510054150/http://www.bbc.co.uk/history/ww2peopleswar/stories/17/a4212217.shtml |archive-date=10 May 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> There was again a clash with fascists in June 1948, when members of the [[43 Group]] and Brighton locals prevented a meeting of [[Oswald Mosley]]'s [[British Union of Fascists]]. What became known as the Battle of the Level ensured no fascists returned to Brighton until the 1960s.<ref name=\"Bance\">{{cite news |last1=Bance |first1=M. |title=Brighton Level History |url=http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Post Magazine |date=1 July 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321231149/http://www.thepostmagazine.co.uk/brightonhistory/brighton-level |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"Greenstein\">{{cite book |last1=Greenstein |first1=Tony |title=Fighting Fascism in Brighton and the South Coast |date=2011 |publisher=Brighton History Workshop |location=Brighton}}</ref>\n\nThe children's [[playground]] was first constructed in 1927 by Bertie Hubbard MacLaren (Superintendent of Parks and Gardens).<ref name=\"Captain\">{{cite web |title=Captain Bertie Hubbard MacClaren |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225924/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-8 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> He added a boating pond and a [[pergola]].  The pond has since been made smaller.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>  During World War II, the [[Royal Engineers]] [[Eminent domain|requisitioned]] the [[Brighton Forum|Chichester Diocesan Training College for Schoolmistresses at Ditchling Road]];<ref name=\"NEB130\">{{Harvnb|Collis|2010|p=130.}}</ref> they put up several [[Nissen hut]]s on The Level to give them more space, and these temporary buildings stayed until well in the the 1950s.<ref name=\"NEB176\"/>\n\n== Recent history ==\n\n===Peace camp===\nBrighton Women\u2019s Peace Camp was set up on the Level on 15 February, 1983, in support of the [[Greenham Common Women's Peace Camp]]. At [[RAF Greenham Common]], women were protesting against [[cruise missile]]s from the USA being placed on British soil. The Brighton camp was one of many short-lived satellite camps that appeared around the United Kingdom in early 1983.<ref name=\"PC\">{{cite journal |last1=Carroll |first1=Sam |title=Brighton Womens Peace Camp, 1983: Second Wave Feminism and the Womens Peace Movement. |journal=University of Sussex Journal of Contemporary History |date=2005 |volume=8 |issue=Winter |url=http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |access-date=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134637/http://sro.sussex.ac.uk/id/eprint/15795/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In contrast to the heavy-handed treatment of campers at Greenham by the authorities, Brighton participants said \"The Brighton Corporation have been very good. And the police have been very good.\"\n<ref name=\"Wimmin\">{{cite news |last1=Davie |first1=Michael |title=Who's afraid of wimmin? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=5 September 2006 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322134844/https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2006/sep/05/greenham3 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===BUFF===\nThe Brighton Urban Free Festival (BUFF) was held on the Level for the first time on September 1, 1984. It was a free music festival which aimed to promote local bands. It occurred again in 1985, then moved to [[Preston Park, Brighton|Preston Park]] in 1986, before returning to the Level in 1987, 1988, 1991 and 1992. Bands which played included [[Peter and the Test Tube Babies]], [[These Animal Men]] and [[Levellers (band)|The Levellers]].<ref name=\"BUFF\">{{cite web |title=Music and performance |url=https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |website=My Brighton and Hove |accessdate=21 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321225913/https://www.mybrightonandhove.org.uk/places/placepark/peoples_history_of_the_level/the-peoples-history-of-the-level-4 |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Skate park ==\n[[File:Brighton,_Skate_Park_(31840008245).jpg|thumb|right|250px|The redeveloped skate park]]\nThe first [[skatepark]] was designed by architects Murrin and Partners and built on the Level in 1978. There was a nearby skateshop called Pig City and in the 1990s there were regular skate competitions.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\">{{cite news |last1=Team |first1=Timeout |title=LOCAL HISTORY: The Level Skatepark in the 1980s |url=https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |accessdate=21 March 2020 |work=The Argus |date=16 August 2018 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321224649/https://www.theargus.co.uk/news/16438921.local-history-the-level-skatepark-in-the-1980s/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> In the early 2000s, an [[elm tree]] next to the skate park became famous for having many shoes thrown into its branches. It then had to be felled in 2018 after catching [[Dutch elm disease]] from elms on the other side of the cycle path.<ref name=\"ShoeTree\">{{cite news |last1=Wadsworth |first1=Jo |title=Level skatepark\u2019s shoe tree to be felled after succumbing to elm disease |url=https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |accessdate=22 March 2020 |work=Brighton and Hove News |date=5 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322124923/https://www.brightonandhovenews.org/2018/07/05/level-skateparks-shoe-tree-to-be-felled-after-succumbing-to-elm-disease/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe council received a lottery grant of \u00a32.2 million to build a new park, which was designed by Freestyle. The new park opened in June 2013.<ref name=\"ArgusSkate\" />\n\n== Redevelopment ==\nFollowing a successful [[National Lottery Heritage Fund]] grant request, the Level was substantially redeveloped from 2009 onwards, expanding MacLaren's original design: the skate park was moved and rebuilt, taking up what had previously been a grassed area; the pavilions were regenerated; the model boating pond was restored with a fountain; the playground was reconfigured; a sensory garden was added; a zone for [[boccia]] and [[p\u00e9tanque]] was provided.<ref name=\"LUC\">{{cite web |title=LUC picks up Sussex Heritage Trust award for The Level in Brighton |url=https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |website=LUC - Environmental Planning, Design and Management |accessdate=22 March 2020 |date=13 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200321222655/https://landuse.co.uk/news/luc-sussex-level-brighton/ |archive-date=21 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"LI\">{{cite web |title=Enhancing Brighton\u2019s Level |url=https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |website=Landscape Institute |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161234/https://www.landscapeinstitute.org/news/enhancing-brightons-level/ |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref> \n\nThe park won a Sussex Heritage Trust award in 2016 and is now [[Green Flag Award]] accreditated.<ref name=\"LUC\" /> It also won a [[Civic Trust Awards|Civic Trust Award]] and National Landscape award.<ref name=\"CTA\">{{cite web |title=The Level |url=https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |website=Civic Trust Awards |accessdate=22 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161233/https://www.civictrustawards.org.uk/winners/the-level1 |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"NLA\">{{cite web |title=National accolade for The Level restoration |url=https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |website=new.brighton-hove.gov.uk |accessdate=22 March 2020 |language=en |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200322161508/https://new.brighton-hove.gov.uk/news/2015/national-accolade-level-restoration |archive-date=22 March 2020 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Antram|first=Nicholas|last2=Morrice|first2=Richard|title=Brighton and Hove|series=Pevsner Architectural Guides|publisher=Yale University Press|location=London|year=2008|isbn=978-0-300-12661-7|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Clunn|first=Harold P.|authorlink=Harold Clunn|title=The Capital-by-the-Sea|year=1953|publisher=The Southern Publishing Co Ltd|location=Brighton|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Collis|f